<h2>Event in February 2018</h2>
<br><br>
<h3>Cold spell during the second half of February</h3>
<br><br>
Due to a shift in the polar vortex a strong high pressure system developed over Scandinavia in the second half of February (see Figure 1 for a weather map during that period). The strong easterly flow brought arctic air into large parts of Europe and caused below average temperatures in most European countries. The number of frost days was twice as high as normal in the Netherlands, France and Iberia (see Section below). The high wind speeds made the feels-like temperatures on some days 5 to 10&#176;C colder. The UK issued heavy weather warnings for the eastern part of the UK for heavy snow showers that formed over the relatively 'warm' North Sea.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/feb2018/Analyse_2018022812.bmp"><img alt="" src="../images/feb2018/Analyse_2018022812.bmp" width="250px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 1: Weather map of 28 February 2018 (Source: KNMI).</em>
<br><br>
This cold spell caused exceptional snow fall in large parts of Europe. For example, Rome was covered in snow for the first time since 2012. This snow <a href="http://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2018/02/26/news/roma_si_sveglia_sotto_la_neve_scuole_chiuse_convocato_operativo_protezione_civile-189768299/?ref=RHPPLF-BH-I0-C8-P1-S1.8-T1#gallery-slider=189766912" target="_blank">resulted</a> in Rome and other Italian cities in trains no longer running and disruption of flights.
<br><br>
The amounts of sunshine in (south)western and northern Europe were much higher due to the mostly dry weather caused by this Easterly flow. The amount of sunshine in the Netherlands was double the normal amount. The UK had almost 40% more sunshine.
<br><br>
<h2>Specific climate indicators for February 2018</h2>
<br><br>
February was characterized by two cold waves, one at the beginning and the other at the end of the month which was also the coldest period of the winter. Central, Northern and Eastern Europe had in February almost 28 days with frost, while southern and western Europe had much less frost days (Figure 2, days with minimum temperature below 0&#176;C). In the Netherlands all locations reported about twice as many frost days as normal, but only normal or below normal number of ice days meaning that the cold stayed longer than normal but was not so extreme. In Germany the number of frost days reached 20-28 days for most of the places (except in the warmer south-west) and about 10 days more than normal. The cold reached also France and Iberia with about twice as many frost days as normal.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/feb2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_fd_2018_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_FD_baselayers_overlay_2018-02-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/feb2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_fd_2018_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_FD_baselayers_overlay_2018-02-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/feb2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_fd_2018_month_nc__2018-02-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/feb2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_fd_2018_month_nc__2018-02-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/feb2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_fd_anom_2018_1981-2010_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_FD_baselayers_overlay_2018-02-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/feb2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_fd_anom_2018_1981-2010_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_FD_baselayers_overlay_2018-02-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/feb2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_fd_anom_2018_1981-2010_month_nc__2018-02-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/feb2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_fd_anom_2018_1981-2010_month_nc__2018-02-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 2: Frost days, days with minimum temperature below 0&#176;C in February 2018 (left) and the difference from the reference period 1981-2010 (right, based on E-OBS).</em>
<br><br>
Ice days (Figure 3, days with maximum temperature below 0&#176;C) in southern Europe are very rare especially at the end of the winter period. Spain and France registered several ice days which is normally not the case. Above normal ice days in Central Europe occurred at higher altitudes as well as in eastern and northern Europe. In northern Europe the temperature remained most of the days below the freezing point. The lowest measured temperature this month occurred in Norway with -42.0&#176;C. Only south-eastern Europe showed above normal temperature with below normal frost and ice days.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/feb2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_id_2018_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_ID_baselayers_overlay_2018-02-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/feb2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_id_2018_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_ID_baselayers_overlay_2018-02-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/feb2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_id_2018_month_nc__2018-02-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/feb2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_id_2018_month_nc__2018-02-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/feb2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_id_anom_2018_1981-2010_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_ID_baselayers_overlay_2018-02-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/feb2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_id_anom_2018_1981-2010_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_ID_baselayers_overlay_2018-02-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/feb2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_id_anom_2018_1981-2010_month_nc__2018-02-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/feb2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_id_anom_2018_1981-2010_month_nc__2018-02-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 3: Ice days, days with maximum temperature below 0&#176;C in February 2018 (left) and the difference from the reference period 1981-2010 (right, based on E-OBS).</em>
<br><br>
A third index describing the cold days is the number of days below the 10th percentile of the daily mean temperature (TG10p, Figure 4). The threshold for this index is defined as the 10th percentile calculated for a 5-day window centered on each calendar day per location in the 1981-2010 reference period. Then the days are counted with daily mean temperature below this threshold. Except for the Crimea and Kola Peninsula, most of Europe showed more than the expected 3 cold days. Especially Iberia, western France, the Alps, Poland, the Baltic states and western Russia had above average numbers of cold days.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/feb2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_tg10p_2018_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_TG10p_baselayers_overlay_2018-02-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/feb2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_tg10p_2018_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_TG10p_baselayers_overlay_2018-02-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
